<section id="tutorial">
  <h2>Complete Guide: How to Create and Implement 301 Redirects</h2>
  
  <article>
    <h3>Understanding 301 Redirects</h3>
    <p>A 301 redirect is the most important tool in your SEO arsenal for handling moved content. When you permanently move a page from one URL to another, a 301 redirect tells both users and search engines where to find the new location. This redirect passes approximately 90-99% of link equity (ranking power) to the new URL, preserving your hard-earned SEO value.</p>
    
    <p>Unlike 302 redirects (temporary) or meta refresh redirects (not recommended for SEO), 301 redirects signal to search engines that the move is permanent. Google and other search engines will transfer the ranking signals, backlinks, and authority from the old URL to the new one, typically within a few weeks.</p>
    
    <h3>When to Use 301 Redirects</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Website Migration:</strong> Moving from one domain to another (e.g., olddomain.com to newdomain.com)</li>
      <li><strong>HTTPS Migration:</strong> Switching from HTTP to HTTPS protocol</li>
      <li><strong>URL Structure Changes:</strong> Changing permalink structure or URL patterns</li>
      <li><strong>Content Consolidation:</strong> Merging multiple pages into one comprehensive page</li>
      <li><strong>Removing Duplicate Content:</strong> Redirecting duplicate pages to the canonical version</li>
      <li><strong>Fixing Broken Links:</strong> Redirecting deleted pages to relevant alternatives</li>
      <li><strong>WWW vs Non-WWW:</strong> Standardizing domain format</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>Step-by-Step Implementation Guide</h3>
    
    <h4>Step 1: Prepare Your Redirect List</h4>
    <p>Before using the generator, create a comprehensive list of URLs that need redirecting. Use tools like Screaming Frog SEO Spider or Google Search Console to identify all pages that need redirects. Create a spreadsheet with two columns: "Old URL" and "New URL". Verify each mapping manually to ensure accuracy.</p>
    
    <h4>Step 2: Choose Your Server Type</h4>
    <p>Identify which server technology your website uses:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Apache:</strong> Most shared hosting, WordPress sites, cPanel servers</li>
      <li><strong>Nginx:</strong> High-performance servers, modern hosting platforms</li>
      <li><strong>PHP:</strong> Dynamic redirects, application-level control</li>
      <li><strong>HTML:</strong> Static sites, emergency fallback method</li>
      <li><strong>JavaScript:</strong> Client-side redirects, single-page applications</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h4>Step 3: Generate Your Redirect Code</h4>
    <p>Use our tool to generate the appropriate redirect code:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Enter your old URL in the "Source URL" field</li>
      <li>Enter your new URL in the "Destination URL" field</li>
      <li>Select your server type from the dropdown</li>
      <li>Configure advanced options if needed (case sensitivity, query strings, etc.)</li>
      <li>Click "Generate Code" to create your redirect</li>
      <li>Review the generated code for accuracy</li>
      <li>Copy or download the code</li>
    </ol>
    
    <h4>Step 4: Implement the Redirects</h4>
    <p><strong>For Apache (.htaccess):</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Connect to your server via FTP or cPanel File Manager</li>
      <li>Navigate to your website's root directory (usually public_html)</li>
      <li>Locate or create the .htaccess file</li>
      <li>Backup the existing .htaccess file</li>
      <li>Paste the generated code at the top of the file (after RewriteEngine On)</li>
      <li>Save the file and upload if using FTP</li>
    </ol>
    
    <p><strong>For Nginx:</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>SSH into your server</li>
      <li>Open your Nginx configuration file: sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/your-site</li>
      <li>Paste the generated code inside the appropriate server block</li>
      <li>Test the configuration: sudo nginx -t</li>
      <li>Reload Nginx: sudo systemctl reload nginx</li>
    </ol>
    
    <h4>Step 5: Test Your Redirects</h4>
    <p>After implementation, thoroughly test each redirect:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Use our built-in redirect tester</li>
      <li>Check HTTP response codes with browser developer tools (should show 301)</li>
      <li>Verify the destination URL is correct</li>
      <li>Test on multiple browsers and devices</li>
      <li>Use online tools like Redirect Checker or HTTP Status Code Checker</li>
      <li>Monitor Google Search Console for crawl errors</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>Common 301 Redirect Mistakes to Avoid</h3>
    
    <h4>1. Redirect Chains</h4>
    <p>Never create redirect chains where URL A redirects to URL B, which redirects to URL C. This dilutes link equity and slows page load times. Always redirect directly to the final destination. Our tool automatically detects and warns about redirect chains.</p>
    
    <h4>2. Circular Redirects</h4>
    <p>Circular redirects create infinite loops (A → B → C → A) that break your website and confuse search engines. Our circular redirect detection algorithm prevents this critical error.</p>
    
    <h4>3. Redirecting to Irrelevant Content</h4>
    <p>Always redirect to the most relevant alternative page. Don't redirect all deleted pages to your homepage—this is called "soft 404" and can harm SEO. If no relevant alternative exists, let the page return a proper 404 error.</p>
    
    <h4>4. Using 302 Instead of 301</h4>
    <p>302 redirects are temporary and don't pass link equity. Always use 301 for permanent moves. Our tool defaults to 301 but allows you to change the redirect type if needed.</p>
    
    <h4>5. Not Updating Internal Links</h4>
    <p>While 301 redirects preserve SEO value, internal links should be updated to point directly to new URLs. This eliminates unnecessary redirects and improves site performance.</p>
    
    <h3>Advanced Redirect Techniques</h3>
    
    <h4>Wildcard Redirects</h4>
    <p>Redirect entire directories or URL patterns using regex wildcards. For example, redirect all blog posts from /blog/* to /articles/* while preserving the post slug.</p>
    
    <h4>Query String Handling</h4>
    <p>Decide whether to preserve or strip query parameters. E-commerce sites often need to preserve parameters like ?product_id=123, while others may want clean URLs.</p>
    
    <h4>Conditional Redirects</h4>
    <p>Create redirects based on conditions like user agent, referrer, or IP address. Useful for mobile redirects or geo-targeting.</p>
    
    <h3>Monitoring and Maintenance</h3>
    <p>After implementing redirects, ongoing monitoring is essential:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Check Google Search Console weekly for crawl errors</li>
      <li>Monitor server logs for 404 errors</li>
      <li>Track organic traffic to redirected pages</li>
      <li>Review redirect performance quarterly</li>
      <li>Remove unnecessary redirects after 1 year (once search engines have fully processed them)</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
