<section id="faq" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About 301 Redirects</h2>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">What is the difference between 301 and 302 redirects?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">A 301 redirect is permanent and tells search engines to transfer all ranking signals to the new URL. A 302 redirect is temporary and tells search engines to keep the original URL indexed. For SEO purposes, always use 301 redirects when permanently moving content. 302 redirects should only be used for temporary situations like A/B testing or seasonal content.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">How long does it take for a 301 redirect to work?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">301 redirects work immediately for users—they'll be redirected instantly. For search engines, it typically takes 2-6 weeks for Google to fully process the redirect and transfer ranking signals. During this time, you may see both old and new URLs in search results. Monitor Google Search Console to track the progress.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Do 301 redirects lose link juice?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">Modern 301 redirects pass nearly 100% of link equity according to Google. In 2016, Google confirmed that 301 redirects don't lose PageRank. However, redirect chains (multiple redirects in sequence) can dilute link equity, so always redirect directly to the final destination URL.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Can I redirect multiple domains to one domain?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">Yes, you can redirect multiple domains to a single primary domain. This is common when consolidating brand variations or after mergers. Use domain-level 301 redirects to point all old domains to your main domain. Make sure to redirect each old URL to its most relevant equivalent on the new domain, not just to the homepage.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Should I redirect deleted pages to the homepage?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">No, redirecting all deleted pages to the homepage is considered a "soft 404" and can harm SEO. Instead, redirect each deleted page to the most relevant alternative content. If no relevant alternative exists, let the page return a proper 404 status code. Search engines prefer honest 404s over irrelevant redirects.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">How many redirects can I have on my website?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">There's no technical limit to the number of 301 redirects you can implement. Large websites commonly have thousands of redirects. However, keep your redirect file organized and remove unnecessary redirects after 1-2 years once search engines have fully processed them. Too many redirects can slightly impact server performance.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">What's the best way to redirect HTTP to HTTPS?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">Use a server-level 301 redirect to force all HTTP traffic to HTTPS. For Apache, add a RewriteCond that checks if HTTPS is off, then redirects to the HTTPS version. For Nginx, use a return 301 statement in the HTTP server block. Our tool generates the exact code for both server types. Also update your canonical tags and internal links to use HTTPS.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Can I use JavaScript for 301 redirects?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">JavaScript redirects using window.location.replace() work for users but aren't true 301 redirects because they happen client-side after the page loads. Search engines may not follow JavaScript redirects reliably. For SEO purposes, always use server-side 301 redirects (Apache, Nginx, or PHP). Use JavaScript redirects only as a last resort or for client-side applications.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">How do I test if my 301 redirect is working?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">Test your 301 redirects using these methods: 1) Use our built-in redirect tester tool, 2) Check browser developer tools Network tab for HTTP 301 status code, 3) Use online tools like Redirect Checker or HTTP Status Code Checker, 4) Use curl command: curl -I https://yoursite.com/old-page, 5) Monitor Google Search Console for crawl errors. The response should show "301 Moved Permanently".</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Should I keep 301 redirects forever?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <p itemprop="text">Keep critical redirects (high-traffic pages, pages with many backlinks) indefinitely. For less important pages, you can remove redirects after 1-2 years once search engines have fully processed them and updated their index. Before removing any redirect, check if it still receives traffic or has active backlinks. Document all redirect removals in case you need to restore them.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
